252	Strategic Plan For Monitoring And Evaluation Of Garbage In The Sea Of The State OfSo Paulo (PEMALM)	Technical Resource	\N	Coastal and marine environments are important providers of ecosystem services, among which  is the regulation of our planets climate. In Brazil, some of the largest cities of the country are found  along the coastline, concentrating intense economic activity that relies on, impacts, and shares space  with a rich, though vulnerable, biodiversity. Recognizing this dynamic is fundamental to think, plan  and act to guarantee a viable future. For FUNBIO, the support to projects aiming for ocean knowledge  and conservation has always been a priority. And it is with great satisfaction that we take part in the  initiative that has generated the present So Paulo Strategic Plan for Monitoring and Assessment  of Marine Litter (PEMALM), a partnership involving the University of So Paulo, the Norwegian  Embassy and the Secretariat of Infrastructure and Environment of the State of So Paulo. Since the early days of its activities, in 1996, FUNBIO has supported the creation and  strengthening of marine and coastal protected areas. This also extends to studies about species, coastal  and marine environments, and fishery resources. The plan represents an important step towards the  creation of an information database in the state of So Paulo, which can subsidize future means to  combat marine litter. A global and growing challenge that requires equally global, and ever-increasing,  knowledge and effort from all of society for mitigation.	\N	\N	\N	{https://drive.google.com/file/d/1GFXQIJjEZ0dRwfeXzun1EoKHP-D8PVMU/view}	\N	2021-04-05 07:08:04.918601+00	2021-04-05 07:08:04.918601+00	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
253	Marine Litter: Guidelines fordesigning action plans	Technical Resource	\N	Marine litter is increasingly an issue requiring urgent transboundary cooperation both at an international and a regional level. The issue is common to all of the worlds oceans. Marine litter and microplastics is found on beaches, floating on the surface of the oceans, suspended in the water column, in sediments and settled on the seabed. Marine litter mostly results from mismanagement of plastic waste at various stages within the lifecycle of products. The processes that result in plastic waste entering the marine environment are broadly the same for all States, but significant differences can also be found.	\N	\N	global	{}	\N	2021-04-05 07:08:04.939503+00	2021-04-05 07:08:04.939503+00	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
254	2019 Hawai'i Marine Debris Action Plan Research Workshop	Action Plan	\N	The Hawaii Marine Debris Action Plan (HI-MDAP) establishes a comprehensive framework for strategic action to reduce the ecological, health and safety, and economic impacts of marine debris in Hawaii by 2020. Goal 5 of the HI-MDAP is to conduct high quality research to understand marine debris. Strategy 1 of the goal is to develop an understanding of marine debris physical and chemical traits, life cycle, transport, quantity, impacts, and accumulation rates of marine debris. Action 5.1.1 is to identify and support marine debris research priorities through a collaborative workshop with a goal for island specific collaboration. To accomplish this action, the first HI-MDAP Research Workshop was held in 2017.In an effort to encourage continued information sharing and collaboration, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Marine Debris Program and the National Institute for Standards and Technology(link is external) partnered to co-facilitate the 2019 HI-MDAP Research Workshop. The workshop was held on July 25-26, 2019 at the Hawaii Pacific University Makapuu Campus.	\N	\N	\N	{https://marinedebris.noaa.gov/file/5244/download?token=nUlhK7Wt}	\N	2021-04-05 07:08:04.957962+00	2021-04-05 07:08:04.957962+00	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	APPROVED	\N	\N	\N
