ide variety of waterways.  Demonstrated Results:On demand collection of floating trash and debris90% capture rateCapable of unattended remote operationUses renewable power sourcesDoes not harm aquatic wildlifeProvides an opportunity for measurement and analysis of storm water pollutants and upstream mitigation effortsProvides an opportunity for educating the public about the problem of plastic pollution and inspires people to become part of the solutionAn attractive means for addressing an unsightly problemLow operating costsDoes not require specialty service equipment or disposable refuse nets or other containersHigh quality construction for reliability and durabilityPerformance:The first Baltimore Trash Wheel was installed in May of 2014 and has removed approximately 200 tons of trash and debris a year, including more than 45 tons from a single storm event.  It is capable of filling an 18 cubic yard dumpster in less than 2 hours and can remove more than 50,000 pounds of solid waste per day.  The profound effect it has had on the harbor has been noted by nearly everyone who lives, works, or recreates there.  This success has led to three more Trash Wheels for Baltimore.Plastic recovery capacity: Trash Wheels have the capacity to capture and remove 50,000 lbs of trash and debris/day. The percentage of plastics depends on the characteristics of the watershed (urban and/or rural0 and ranges from 20 to 80 percent.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.122835+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.122835+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.mrtrashwheel.com/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_055.png	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_55_logo.jpeg	\N
