60	Ho'ola One: A power tool that collects the small waste accumulated on the Kam ilo beach	\N	42	Academic Institution	Pilot	f	info@hoolaone.com	national	{}	Ho'ola one works towards removing microplastics from the environment of the beach. Twelve engineering students at the University of Sherbrooke in Quebec built a machine for the organization that isolates plastic pieces from the sandy beaches. For several years, the plastic waste that ends on Kamilo Beach has been breaking down into increasingly fine particles. Through the years the Hawai'i Wildlife Fund has managed to dump the bulky debris, but it's the small stuff left behind buried in the sand, that's the remaining problem. Animals confuse plastic particles with insects or other living organisms and ingest them. Plastic therefore enters the food chain and poisons it. The Ho'ola One project team aims to help combat this problem.At University of Sherbrooke, twelve mechanical engineering students have been devoted to this major design project for the last two years of their degree. Leatherman, an aquatic biologist and President of the Hawai'i Wildlife Fund, believes the 'Ho'ola One' - a sand like vacuum designed by Canadian engineering students, is the solution. The machine has a big vacuum that collects the mix of sand and plastics, once the sand is dropped into a water tank, the sand sinks and the plastic floats. The machine works by separating the plastic parts from sand using the density of the diverse components. The plastic pieces are often too small to be handpicked, however with the help of the machine the minute plastic particles are picked.The device has removed roughly 230-pounds of micro-plastics at Kamilo Point (in Hawa) in a matter of days.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.263683+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.263683+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://hoolaone.com/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_060.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_60_logo.png	\N
61	Ocean Polymers: Building a plastic recycling plant in the ocean to convert plastic into power.	2017	83	Startup	Research	f	info@oceanpolymers.co.uk	national	{}	Ocean Polymers is committed to turning plastic waste into a valuable resource. The startup is constructing a tanker, named OP3 with a gasification system that has the capacity of processing 200 tons of plastic and waste per day thanks to its onboard machinery which recycles plastic found in the ocean and converts it into hydrogen to power the station. The firm has been working with a team from Imperial College London on the project for the past six years, and it hopes to get up and running in the second half of 2019. During the recycling process on the ship, valuable products such as hydrogen, synthetic gases, building materials and substrates will be created. Their systems will not only remove plastics which are harmful to marine wildlife and enter the food chain but it is self-funding when operating, as a result of the valuable bi-products created.The project will involve smaller boats traveling short distances to take rubbish back to the main ship. Ocean Polymers has secured the patent pending status that has been granted by the US Patent Office on 14th May 2019.  They are in the process of securing intellectual property rights and developing a business plan.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.28714+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.28714+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.cleanourocean.com	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_061.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_61_logo.png	\N
62	OceanCycle: Certification for ocean-bound plastics	2018	253	Startup	In market	t	info@oceancycle.co	national	{}	Description: Currently our system is diverting over 1,500 MT of plastic per month from our oceans and this material is actually being used. Products range from packaging to textiles to engineering grade resins. Materials are being used in Europe, the US, and Asia. Our systems approach is deigned for scale and cost and has the ability to triple capacity right away. Available materials are PET, PP, and PEPlastic recovery capacity: Metric tons. Currently, we divert about 1,500 MT per month. We could scale to 5,000 within 1-2 months and 10,000 within 4-5 months (COVID travel dependent).	2021-04-05 07:08:08.334418+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.334418+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.oceancycle.co/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_062.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_62_logo.jpeg	\N
69	Ashored: Innovations for profitable and sustainable ocean harvests	\N	42	Startup	In market	f	info@ashored.ca	national	{}	Ashored develops sustainability-enabling technologies for the commercial fishing industry. Ashored is currently developing a rope on-command (ROC) fishing system to minimize the risk of whale entanglements and trap loss/damage, while allowing fishers to fish in zones closed to fixed fishing gear. Marine animal entanglements and ghost fishing are creating huge issues in oceans. Entanglements are the leading cause of death for North Atlantic Right Whales and 83% of the population has visible scars from fishing gear entanglement. To remedy this, Ashored is developing new fishing systems to allow fishing to continue while creating safer conditions for whales.Ashoreds underwater buoy/rope releases work with existing lobster/crab traps/trawl lines and allow for said gear to be activated via acoustics (or a backup timer) to the surface. Once the buoy and connecting rope rise to the surface, fishermen can use existing onboard equipment and processes to retrieve the gear and prepare it for redeployment. Ashoreds ROC fishing systems include a rope containment and release module (MOBI) that also uses sensors to collect and transmit data to an onboard gear tracking system (ATLAS). ATLAS consists of Ashoreds ATLAS+ software and smart tagging to reduce gear loss and allow fishers to automate the tracking of gear and logging of catch information.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.677059+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.677059+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://ashored.ca/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_069.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_69_logo.jpeg	\N
63	Planet Patrol App: Paddleboarding for a cause: to rid our waterways of plastic pollution	2016	83	Non-Profit Org	Pilot	f	\N	national	{}	Planet Patrol is a charity with an aim to rid the inland waterways of intense plastic pollution, using the collaborative power of community action coupled with the use of disruptive technology to acquire data for research in developing sustainable alternatives.Plastic pollution is becoming an increasingly critical crisis, upsetting food chains and disrupting entire ecosystems. By 2050, the weight of plastic dumped in the ocean is projected to be twice the weight of all the fish and marine life living in it. Single-use plastic is a major source of the plastic crisis, with a mere 1% of single-use plastic bags being returned for recycling and with an average life cycle of just 12 minutes. Inland waterways are usually the origin for dumping waste plastic, which travels and find their way into the oceans. Planet Patrol launched to tackle this environmental catastrophe by organising community-driven clean-ups and collecting data on plastic pollution data using the Planet Patrol App. Every clean-up brings communities together, where waste is seen, photographed, shared on the app and cleared away; serving an equivocal purpose of helping the environment and acquisition of data. The data collected is used for scientific research into waste that escapes into nature, and helps stop the pollution at the first point of contact with the environment. The Planet Patrol app is a real-world tool that provides a platform for data collection and sharing along with community interaction; done by combining the power of citizen science and scientific analysis. The app will enable Planet Patrol to record and analyze data to conduct the world's largest survey of inland plastic pollution, with the River Thames in London alone carrying 18 tonnes of plastic. The users are required to categorize each piece by type and brand before uploading the photos. The app also aids in building a worldwide community of environmentally aware individuals, actively working towards eliminating plastic from our waterways through a collaborative effort. Nearly 300,000 pieces of plastic have been logged from over 80 countries using the #PlanetPatrol App, having intercepted 440 tonnes of plastic waste from inland waterways; that is equivalent to 15 million water bottles. They also organise corporate clean-ups and workshops to accelerate the process of eliminating single-use plastics and embed sustainability in workplaces.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.384376+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.384376+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://planetpatrol.co/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_063.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_63_logo.png	\N
64	Plastic Odyssey: The Expedition Around The World To Fight Against Plastic Pollution	2017	79	Non-Profit Org	Development	f	expedition@plasticodyssey.org	national	{}	Plastic Odyssey is a non-profit organization that aims to fight against plastic pollution by acting at the source: ashore. Their vision? Build a global network of local initiatives. Their ambition? Clean up the past and build the future!How? By encouraging social entrepreneurship at the local level, developing low-tech and open source technologies, and stimulating social engagement to empower local communities.Their means? A 40 meters laboratory vessel, ambassador for the reduction and recycling of plastic waste that conceives, creates and develops simple solutions accessible to all, to reduce plastic pollution in the Ocean. Their ship will leave in early 2021 for a 3-year expedition across 3 continents, and over 30 cities, to uncover and share solutions.The vessel, which embodies a real life-size demonstration platform to assess and promote tomorrows solutions, will circumnavigate along the worlds most polluted coasts to reconcile global challenges with local development. Onboard will be displayed:Low-tech and open source technologies to recycle plastic wasteA mobile nomadic village to share knowledge and action tools with the remotestTo give you a little more perspective on the journey of their project, here are their stopovers:2021: Lebanon, Egypt, Tunisia, Algeria, Morocco, Senegal, Guinea, Brazil, Haiti, Costa Rica, Ecuador2022: Peru, Polynesia, Fiji, Papua New Guinea, Indonesia, Philippines, Vietnam, Malaysia, Indonesia2023: Thailand, Myanmar, India, Sri Lanka, Maldives, Madagascar, Mozambique, South Africa, Angola, Ivory Coast. You can find out more about their stopovers HERE.  Their sponsors:Main partner: LOccitane en ProvenceOfficial partners: Crdit Agricole, Clarins, MatmutSocial partners: Enowe, BiodermaPatrons: Veolia, Procapital, Ponant: Fondation Ocans Ples-Peuples, Octopus Invest, PaxArctica, FeelingoTechnical partners: Setec, The Dung Beetle Project, Trivo, InsaValor, Bee EngineeringMedia Partners: Springwise, Bonne Pioche, RFIOfficial suppliers and service providers: Marlink, Stephenson Hardwood, Smart Sailors, Sofresid, Latham WatkinsAre you are representative of a company, an association, or an institution, and wish to commit yourself to their project? Become a partner of the project! They need you to make this adventure possible and build a world free of plastic in the Ocean.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.42345+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.42345+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://plasticodyssey.org/en/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_064.jpeg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_64_logo.png	\N
65	Safegear: Partnership to fight ghost gear	2010	83	Non-Profit Org	Research	f	info@bluemarinefoundation.com	national	{}	The Blue Marine Foundation (BLUE) is a charity dedicated to creating marine reserves and establishing sustainable models of fishing. Blue's aim is to put 10% of the worlds oceans under protection by 2020 and 30% by 2030. They also work to establish sustainable fisheries so fish stocks can begin to recover.Over-fishing represents a major food security issue and has devastating consequences for the fragile biodiversity of our planet. Around 90% of global fish stocks are fully or over-exploited and around 90% of large fish are gone. The consequences are far-reaching, not only for the future of food for a growing global population, but because healthy oceans absorb half the CO2 we produce, this led them come up with The Blue Marine Foundation.Every year, an estimated 640,000 tons of fishing gear is lost in the oceans around the world. Safegear offers a simple solution to stop this plastic pollution.Beacons are being designed to fit onto existing fishing gear markers that normally comprise of a float, bamboo pole, and flag. It allows fishing vessels to inexpensively monitor their gear at sea, receive alerts if the gear starts to move, and contact vessels in the area. If gear is lost due to towing or bad weather, the beacon allows the fishing vessel to track the gear and recover it.These electronic beacons will also allow the fishing gear markers to be viewed on the bridge, wheelhouse and cockpit plotters of other marine traffic so they can avoid the hazard. Existing markers are almost impossible to see at night and often difficult in daylight.The Blue Marine Foundation has won various awards and recognitions -In 2014 BLUE won NGO of the Year in the PEA (People Environment Achievement) Awards in recognition that it was getting results where they matter most. In 2015 BLUE won four PEA Awards as part of the GB Oceans Coalition including Overall Champion.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.577899+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.577899+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://www.bluemarinefoundation.com	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_065.jpg	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_65_logo.jpg	\N
66	SeaChange: Converting ocean plastics to inert, non-toxic glass safe for marine life	\N	253	Non-Profit Org	Prototype	f	media@theseachange.org	national	{}	SeaChange is seeking to solve the marine plastics problem and create an end game for ocean plastics.Only 9% of the 400 million tons of plastic produced globally each year is recycled. Much of that unrecycled plastic ends up in oceans with approximately one dump truck load of plastic is put into the ocean every minute. When exposed to the sun, these plastics can degrade into harmful microplastics. SeaChange wants to act before this can happen and stop the pollution cycle by removing plastics from the waste stream.Using a plasma enhanced melter (PEM), SeaChange wants to collect ocean plastics and convert them into a non-toxic, inert glass that is safe for humans and marine life. The PEM breaks down the molecular structure of plastics at temperatures up to 18,000F. The process converts 5 tons of plastic a day into clean syngas and glass. The syngas can be used for fuel. SeaChange plans on utilizing the PEM technology on ships that can be deployed in areas with a large amount of plastic waste.Phase 1 of their mission is focused on deploying SeaChange ships in the Indonesian archipelago where 1.42 million tons of plastic leak into the ocean every year. SeaChange utilizes InEnTec's PEM system.	2021-04-05 07:08:08.611457+00	2021-04-05 07:08:08.611457+00	\N	\N	APPROVED	https://theseachange.org/	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_066.PNG	https://storage.googleapis.com/akvo-unep-gpml/images/technology_66_logo.jpeg	\N
